About
The Palau, an icon of modernist architecture in downtown Barcelona The Palau de la Música Catalana is one of the most representative monuments of the city and It is one of the most recommended tourist attractions of Barcelona. Built between 1905 and 1908 by the great architect Lluis Domènech i Montaner, the Palau de la Música Catalana is an architectural jewel of Catalonia and essential part of any visit to the city, as any of the most fascinating Gaudi buildings. This historical building, declared a World Heritage Site by UNESCO in 1997, offers an experience so magical that visitors fall in love with it. From the hand of experienced guides, the wonders of this architectural pearl discovered and visitors into a fantasy world full of details and references to the characteristic nature of modernist architecture. An essential visit in the list of top 10 things to see in Barcelona.
Duration: < 1 hour

The area

Address
Neighborhood: El Born / La Ribera
The labyrinth that is El Born becomes most apparent the moment you turn down one of its side streets. But this is one of the few labyrinths you might actually enjoy losing your way in. After all, there are few places that live and breathe such exciting energy regardless of the time of day. This neighborhood seamlessly transcends the old and new parts of the city, reflected in its vast array of restaurants ranging from fancy Michelin-star establishments to trendy fusion restaurants. Here you'll find historical and cultural attractions such as the popular Picasso Museum and the Gothic cathedral La Santa Maria del Mar, where you just might be able to catch a traditional Catalan wedding.
How to get there
  • Urquinaona • 3 min walk
  • Catalunya • 6 min walk

    So beautiful and cheerful
    There are so many things to do in Barcelona that you might forget about the Palace of Catalan Music in the Gothic Quarter not far from the cathedral. But you'd miss out on a unique window into Catalan culture if you did. The auditorium itself is one of the richest and most beautiful in Europe; they say that the acoustics in it are quite special. The colors are fabulous: rich and vibrant. Sit and take it all in! There is also a nice cafe inside the Palace and a small gift shop. For 2 euros more, I recommend the guided tour: you'll get to hear the magnificent organ and you'll get a lot of insight into the architect's vision.

    Modernism at its maximum power
    The "Palau de la Musica Catalana" is a concert hall that was built in Modernist style between 1905 and 1908. It is not big, but there are so many amazing details that it can take some time to see it all: the main façade, the foyer, the staircases, the Luis Millet Hall, the main concert hall, the bar. In 1997, the palace de la Música Catalana was declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

  • CourtneyStanz
    Belle Mead, New Jersey129 contributions
    Do not miss this experience
    We visited the Palau Musica on 11/26 for a Flamenco Guitar program, and it was an afternoon that will live in our family's memory forever. As all of the photos convey, the Palau is breathtakingly beautiful. The Art Nouveau attention to detail is evident in every corner, handle, light switch, and finish. Nothing can prepare you for the grandeur and aesthetic overwhelm. It is heaven for art, architecture, and history lovers. Beyond the visual stimuli, the acoustics are heavenly and the show was incredible. While our family is American, we were visiting with an expat family member and their Catalan partner - each of us found the afternoon to be delightful in every sense. Next time, I'd love to take a tour and better understand the history, recurring themes, and construction. But I cannot recommend more highly seeing/hearing a show in the space if your time in Barcelona allows. It will be a treasured memory!

  • TheLeongOhana
    United States7,548 contributions
    Just Beautiful
    We decided at the last minute to visit and got lucky by joining the last guided tour of the day. It started with a movie in the Petit Palau. We then walked into the original building to visit the foyer. However a private event precluded us from entering and fully seeing it. We climbed the grand staircase and then entered the amazing concert hall. The central skylight up above was truly a sight to see. Even with the storm clouds outside it still let in a lot of light. The decor was modernism that also incorporated musical muses and so glad we could see a lot of it up close. We were also allowed to walk on stage as our guide continued the tour and then setup for a demonstration of the massive organ. The sound was beautiful and hopefully we can come back to enjoy an actual concert. The Lluis Millet Hall was one floor above the concert hall and contained a special art exhibit. Outside was the balcony where many instagrammable photos were taken with the beautiful mosaic columns. We finished the tour on the balcony over looking the concert hall which was a great perspective to see its entirety. We did find the seats not very comfortable though! Outside the fascade of the Palau was also a must see including the statues of many famous composers. It was not as easy to see all the details due to the surrounding buildings and tight street. Our guide used the 2nd floor balcony to point out details in the reflections to the opposite building’s windows. This should be a must see when in Barcelona. Well worth the time to see this UNESCO designated building.

    Amazing experience, catch a live concert if you can.
    We had been planning on booking a tour but when we found a guitar and flamenco concert for the last night of our trip we booked it immediately. We paid €42 each for stall seats, the concert was about 90-110 minutes ( no interval) and it flew by. The music was phenomenal, the dancing superb (especially the male dancer) and the encore was astounding - have you ever seen three guitarists and a percussionist play a Michael Jackson melody on ONE guitar??! The building itself is stunning, and I would like to return in daylight to get the effect of the natural light. Hoever it was nice to see it being used for its proper purpose, not just a museum. The bar/ restaurant looked interesting but of course was very busy.

    The Heartbeat of Barcelona Culture
    This place is simply amazing. There are 3 reasons to visit here. First, the palace and concert hall are architectural marvels, treating you to sights and sounds you have never seen or heard before. Second, catching a performance here is very special. We were not able to attend an event in the main hall, but thoroughly enjoyed a classical music concert in the smaller venue. It was outstanding! Third, they feature a really high quality gift shop and a top notch restaurant as well. If in Barcelona, the Palau de la Musica is a must do. The Most Beautiful Building in Barcelona
Oct 2024 • Couples
I'd seen pictures of this venue online and wanted to see it in person. One day we arrived after 3 pm and saw the outside, but learned to do an inside tour, we'd need to arrive earlier as they stop doing tours once it's time for people to arrive for performances. We came back and did a 2 pm tour the next day. The tour guide was very knowledgeable. This venue is absolutely beautiful inside, with sculpture, stained glass, and lots of beautiful and practical artistry. They have a program to play the massive organ, and you can tell that the acoustics here are spectacular.
All of the icons are music related, from the names of classical composers on the ceiling to callbacks for characters and situations from classical pieces. It is well worth the entry fee. If we'd had more time, we'd have gone to a concert.

What are the Category A and B best seats for the Flamenco performance at Palau de la Música
Written August 28, 2023
Patricia B
20 contributions
The quality of the seats depends upon how much you pay. Category B costs 35 Euros; Category A is 42 Euros; VIP seats cost 55 Euros; Premium seats cost 75 Euros. Go to the Palace of Music website to view the seating chart. The less a seat costs, the farther from the stage. Posts blocking your view from some of the cheaper seats. We were in box 8 on the right side of the stage. Each box has 7 seats - three in the front (Premium seats), 2 in the second elevated row (VIP) and 2 in the third elevated row (VIP). The box and the seats are very small and next to each other in the first row. The view and sound from where we were seating in the elevated second row were fantastic.
